I oppose this nomination, and if it is withdrawn or voted down, I will be ready that day to work with this White House on finding nominees from Nevada that are qualified and fair and nonpartisan. 

The people of Nevada – particularly today, on Nevada Day, deserve nothing less.

If that all isn’t enough, here’s one more thing to consider – the American Bar Association has, by a substantial majority, rated Mr. VanDyke as "Not Qualified." 

For a lifetime appointment, we should always strive for a candidate that is very qualified.

I’m also concerned about comments Mr. VanDyke has made about LGBTQ Americans. 

In 2004, Mr. VanDyke wrote that there is quote: “ample reason for concern that same-sex marriage will hurt families, and consequentially children and society.”

Among the briefs Mr. VanDyke signed his home state of Montana onto during his tenure as Solicitor General, was one asking the Supreme Court to strike down Roe v. Wade, and all of the reproductive rights cases that followed Roe.

Mr. VanDyke – a Montana native who ran for office there and also worked in Texas – came to Nevada for a job in 2015, and when the person he worked for lost a political race in 2018, he quickly sold the house he briefly owned in Nevada and moved to Virginia to work in DC.

As @SenatorLankford and I launch this new initiative to combat anti-Semitism, we look forward to collaborating with the House Bipartisan Task Force for Combating Anti-Semitism, led by @NitaLowey and @RepChrisSmith, to work across chambers and party lines to fight hate.

To be clear: this will be a bipartisan task force because combating hate is a nonpartisan issue. 

During a time when anti-Semitism is on the rise, it’s vital that we not allow ideology or partisanship to blur our perspective about right and wrong.
We will work to call out hate, support legislative efforts to combat anti-Semitism, promote Holocaust education, and bring this issue to the forefront of our national conversation.

As Members of Congress, it is our responsibility to work together to prevent anti-Semitism before it starts. 

The mission of the Task Force will be to collaborate with government, law enforcement, educators, advocates, clergy, and others to educate, explain, & empower.

One year after the anti-Semitic acts of hate in Pittsburgh, I’m saying enough is enough. 

I’m announcing my Bipartisan Task Force for Combating Anti-Semitism with @SenatorLankford. https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/28/opinions/senate-task-force-to-combat-anti-semitism-rosen-lankford/index.html …

As my first action while holding the floor of the United States Senate, I’m asking Senate leaders to take up my resolution with @Sen_JoeMachin to defend the constitutionality of the ACA. Nevadans sent me here to protect their health care. That’s what I’ll continue to do.
There are plenty of ways that we can work to improve the Affordable Care Act, but destroying the law and leaving Americans at risk is simply unacceptable.

If the Administration has its way with invalidating our health care law, it would spell disaster for millions who rely on access to quality, affordable care. Over 1.2 million Nevadans live with a pre-existing condition. We all know what’s at stake.

But there’s no issue that matters more to Nevada’s hardworking families than health care. From Las Vegas to Elko, I’ve met with countless Nevadans who tell me what it means to not have to fear being denied coverage based on a pre-existing condition.

✅Protecting our environment and public lands
✅Embracing clean energy
✅Honoring our heroes and their families
✅Supporting economic growth
✅Investing in our children’s education 
These are just some of the issues we can work on together – across the aisle – and improve lives.

If there’s any issue that threatens Nevada’s beautiful landscapes and the people who call our state home, it’s Yucca Mountain. 
   
Mark my words, Nevadans’ voices matter. We do NOT consent to this ill-conceived project.

Not now. Not ever.

I placed holds last month on 2 DHS nominees until conditions for migrant children at the border improve.

After my visit, it's clear they haven't. This morning I sent a letter to @DHSMcAleenan outlining 3 needed reforms. Until these reforms are implemented, my holds will remain. pic.twitter.com/fJP75U5XIS

We owe it to migrant children and families to reach an immediate solution. We owe it to our law enforcement to prevent this difficult situation from continuing. 

We must come together, and we must take action. Now.
Once we’ve taken the necessary steps to ensure these children are in safe and sanitary conditions, then we must take up the long-overdue task of reforming our long-term immigration policy.
The evidence is clear: conditions at these facilities have not improved, and until they do, I will not remove my holds on this Administration’s nominees.

I refuse to stand by while this takes place on American soil. So I took action by placing holds on two individuals nominated to serve in administrative and policy roles at DHS until conditions in these facilities drastically improve.

We saw children stuffed into crowded spaces. The people detained in these facilities lack access to basic necessities like toothpaste and access to sanitary supplies. There are few, if any, pediatricians. No child welfare professionals. No hope.

Families are still being separated. Traumatized children are still in cages, and this Administration continues to ignore basic human rights. Children should never be held in these conditions under any circumstance, for any amount of time. Period.

Children and their families are coming to our country for the same reason so many of our ancestors did – because they have no other choice. We are a nation of immigrants built on a foundation of core values, and we do not turn away those fleeing persecution.

Make no mistake about it: there is a humanitarian crisis at our southern border, and we are failing to address it. 

This Administration is failing to address it. This Congress is failing to address it. https://twitter.com/i/broadcasts/1mrxmvEYAELKy …
I’m about to take to the Senate floor at 11:30AM ET/8:30AM PT to share what I saw at the border last week and what we need to begin to address this humanitarian crisis.
Last month, I placed holds on two DHS nominees until conditions in facilities like McAllen drastically improve to meet the standards DHS is obligated to uphold.
We need child welfare professionals in these facilities, and we need more pediatricians and medical professionals. The situation is dire.
I heard from families who have no idea when they’ll be released. They’re scared. Some have open cases in immigration court, and some don’t. Our system is failing these families.

Detaining families in these conditions goes against our values. We need to immediately improve conditions for children and families, and then address our long-term immigration policy. We must do better. pic.twitter.com/URJ4gU352X

I can’t stop thinking about what I saw last week at the border.
